name: ThinkFun Codemaster Game
desc: Product Description Code Master is a puzzle board game that takes players on the ultimate coding adventure. Players learn how to step through code to understand the logic and sequence behind a computers actions. Players will be entertained while developing an understanding of computer programming principles - no computer required. Perfect for parents wanting to increase their childrens interest in computer programming in line with the current national curriculum by making coding exciting and building a childs understanding of key concepts.With ThinkFuns Code Master players learn the fundamentals of computer programming logic in a fun and entertaining way. On each level players program an avatar to harvest power crystals and reach the destination portal. The program is written using a flowchart called a Guide Scroll which illustrates the shape of the required program. Players must think carefully because only one specific sequence of actions will lead to success. Code Masters rules of program execution help kids understand how a real computer executes programs building a powerful mental model of how computers operate. The games 60 logic puzzles for ages 8 and up gradually increase in difficulty introducing fundamental programming concepts and strengthening a childs ability to think like a computer and visualize the outcome of their coded instructions. Box Contains 1 - Avatar1 - Portal6 - Crystals10 Maps with 60 Levels12 - Guide Scrolls12 - Action Tokens8 - Conditional TokensInstruction Manual with Solutions

name: Luxurious Dominoes Double 9 Set - Mahogany Cased - Luxury Dominoes Set
desc: If you have ever played Dominoes double 6 you will simply love the set of Dominoes double 9 from Jaques of London! name: Paul Lamond Dear Zoo Dominoes
desc: Product Description If the Dear Zoo storybook is a roaring success in your house then why not give your little one a gift which stars their favourite animal characters and helps them recognise colours and numbers? The Dear Zoo Dominoes are a great game for both pre-school girls and boys aged three upwards. Cracking for Christmas and brilliant for birthdays these bright and colourful dominoes will keep children entertained for hours whilst helping the development of hand-eye coordination matching and organisation skills. Each of the cheerfully illustrated dominoes features characters from Rod Campbells classic lift-flap storybook loved by children for more than three decades now. Any child who has read Dear Zoo will love the story of how a child writes to the zoo asking for a pet. A series of unsuitable pets are dispatched until the last page when the perfect pet arrives. From two swinging monkeys and six grey elephants to two lions and five slithering snakes each domino features two sets of animals on a bold coloured background ready for pre-school matching fun. Dear Zoo Dominoes are great way to encourage your child to interact and communicate with whoever theyre playing with. Theyll also learn to negotiate rules take turns and problem solves - all whilst having fun with the educational and entertaining Dear Zoo Dominoes! The perfect pet might be hard to find but the Dear Zoo Dominoes are a winning gift for game-loving pre-schoolers. Box Contains 1 x Assorted dominoe pieces

name: Harry Hastings How Well Do You Know Your Monarchs?
desc: How Well Do You Know Your Monarchs is the original History Heroes games invented by history teacher (and now Brighton College Prep headmaster) Harry Hastings. The game has 42 cards each depicting an individual English monarch from 1066 to the present day. You win a card by guessing the monarch from their image or facts read out. You win the game by winning the most cards. You can play the game in the classroom the playground at the airport on the train or around the kitchen table at home. The facts range from green easiest to red most difficult so you can play with all ages and stages of knowledge within the same game. How Well Do You Know Your Monarch is wittily illustrated by well-known cartoonist Bill Stott Review This card game based on the rulers of England is a great travel toy - beautifully illustrated by Bill Stott and compiled by Sussex-based history teacher Harry Hastings. Its playable on all different levels with six games in total ranging from Top Trumps - based on length of reigns - for younger children to guessing the king/queen/protector based on a few hints. -Catherine H Mumsnet Review

name: Storyonics - Magical Mystery Stories: 6 - 106 years
desc: A picture paints a thousand words! What story will you tell? The game is wonderfully simple. Having dealt out the deck the first player chooses one of the four colour images on their card and starts a story inspired by the image. The next player chooses any image from their card and continues the story linking the images in some way. There are no rules and players can interpret the images in any way they choose allowing all ages to play. The story tellers can be as creative as they wish and there is usually much hilarity particularly after dinner! Alternatively there is a competitive version of the game where players take it in turns to tell a story against the clock (sand timer included) winning the cards they incorporate successfully. Read the e-book Hello Kittys Surprise to find out how Hello Kitty spent her birthday or join in the celebration and play one of three party-themed touchscreen learning games. name: Orchard Toys Slug in a Jug
desc: Product Description The 48 rhyming cards in this box can be used to play 3 different versions of this game. In version one players each choose a card and have to pick another from the cards spread face down on the table that rhymes with the one they have chosen. The aim is to make as many rhyming pairs as they can and they have to make up a sentence using the cards that they have. They can increase their scores by collecting three or four rhyming cards but must make up a sentence using all the rhyming cards they have. Once they have a rhyming pair players can continue by taking more cards from the middle aiming to produce more rhymes. The winner is the person with the highest score. In the second version of the game players try to match the word from the top of a pile by turning over unseen cards on the table collecting pairs that rhyme as they go. The winner is the person with the most rhyming pairs at the end of the game. In the third game players each take a hand of two cards and pick unseen cards from the table which they hope will rhyme with one of the cards in their hand. If they find a rhyming pair they put the pair to one side and pick another to bring their hand back up to two cards. The winner is the player with the most rhyming pairs at the end of the game. This puzzle approximately 61cms x 42cms when complete is beautifully illustrated with lots of detail and plenty to talk about. It has just 25 pieces so is particularly suited to children aged between 3 and 6. Before starting the puzzle you can encourage your child to look for pieces with different things on: can you find a piece with a chimney? Can you see a piece with a cat on? Can you see a piece with something green on? Later when the puzzle is complete you will see many things going on in the picture to talk about: what room is the broom in? What colour is the teddy bear on the bed? How many animals can you see in the house? What is in the bowl on top of the fridge? The picture is full of lots of familiar household objects that children will be able to identify from their own home. There is an activity guide on the base of the box to suggest other ways of extending the play value of the puzzle. The puzzle is made from thick durable recycled board so will give many years of fun. name: Orchard Toys Once Upon a Time Dominoes

The dominoes printed on sturdy recycled board show pictures of dragons flying pink unicorns mermaids princesses pixies friendly witches and fairy Godmothers. The cards are dealt to the players and the remaining ones are placed in a pile face down on the table. The first player puts one of their dominoes face up on the table and subsequent players try to match a picture from one of the dominoes in their hand to one at either end of the line of dominoes on the table. The winner is the first person to play all their dominoes or if nobody can finish the player with the fewest dominoes at the end of the game. The game is very simple and as it relies solely on pictures even younger children may be able to join in successfully. The game can help with counting colour recognition and number and language awareness you can increase the play value of the game by asking your child questions about the pictures on the dominoes: what does the fairy Godmother have in her hand? What colour is the princesss dress? Can you find a card with a mermaid and a pixie on it? The dominoes are made of sturdy re-cycled board and the game can be played by 2 to 4 players. name: Orchard Toys Farmyard Dominoes

The game is extremely simple making it perfect for young children aged between 3 and 9. The colourful cards are dealt to each player and the first player starts the game by placing one of their cards in the centre of the table. Subsequent players have to try and match a card from their hand to one of the pictures at either end of the line of dominoes on the table. If at any time a player cant put one of his dominoes down they must pick a new card up from the pile and play passes to the next player. The winner is the first person to play all their dominoes or the one with the fewest dominoes left at the end of the game. Children will love the attractive illustrations and bold colours and can add fun to the game by making the relevant animal noises as they lay their cards down. You can encourage your child to talk about the animals on the cards: which animal gives us milk? Which one gives us eggs? They can also be used to help colour recognition and to practise counting: what colour is the goat on? How many chickens can you count on the table? Can you find me a card with a dog and a horse on? A player simply picks a card and studies it for 10 seconds before being asked a question from the back chosen by the roll of a die. A correct answer means the card is kept if not it is returned to the box. The player with most cards after 5 or 10 minutes wins! The winner may not be who you expect as this fabulous game is about observation and memory not learned facts! Experiment with light and the colour spectrum by building a colour wheel a fibre optic peacock and diffraction glasses. Learn how the eye and a camera are similar and how they are different. Build a camera obscurer and pinhole glasses. Investigate lenses and light refraction. Experiment with spatial vision and depth perception with 3D glasses and an Ames room model. The excitement builds as you have fewer and fewer cards left to play but less space to play them in as you reach the table’s edge! Every county card is different and hence no two games are ever the same in this clever game that you will want to play again and again. name: 24 Game Double Digits - 48 Card Pack
desc: The 24-Game is a maths card game using puzzle cards. It is available as either 48 cards in a pack or 96 cards in a sturdy box. The cards are large (approx 12cm square) and very high quality. This maths game is very easy to start as there is always only one rule: use all 4 numbers with any operation (add subtract multiply divide) to make 24. There are a wide range of sets to cater for increasing levels of difficulty: (a) Single digits then double digits (b) One of the numbers is a fraction or a decimal (c) Some or all of the numbers are negative (d) One of the numbers is shown as an algebraic expression! The game can be played in many different ways but conventionally the cards are placed face up on the table. All players compete for the top card. The first to solve the card claims it and play moves on to the next card. However the game can be played collaboratively as well. As players experience increases they get quicker and better at sorting the numbers and finding combinations of them which can build up to 24. The game does much more than practice the four rules. Instead it emphasises the all important thinking time when players quickly test the options developing key problem solving skills. Cards have three levels of difficulty: 1 Dot = easy 2 Dot = medium 3 Dot = tough. This set is the 48 card pack with single and double digit numbers.

The next player - to the players left - tries to match one of his tiles with the one in the centre. The game continues in this way as each player takes a turn to try to create a chain of tiles. desc: Product Description My First Clock is a colourful supersize clock (30cm) that teaches so many things not just how to tell the time! Playing with My First Clock teaches all about numbers counting colours shapes and sequencing in addition to introducing children to a variety of different fruits and vegetables. The clock is made up of four parts that connect together with a secure Velcro-style fastening. An additional piece provides moveable clock hands. In addition to the clock parts the set contains three different sets of pieces to attach around the perimeter of the clock that provide lots of activities with educational value. The first group is a set of round pieces of identical size with different coloured backgrounds and featuring the numbers 1 - 12. For the simplest first activity a child should begin with this set and match the colours on the circles to the colour s of the numbers on the clock. By simply matching the colours the numbers will be positioned correctly on the clock face. The next stage uses the set of numbers that are printed on different shaped pieces which also feature different patterns. In order to position these pieces correctly a child needs to look closely at the shape of the numbers and match these to the numbers on the clock face. The third set of pieces features different quantities of fruits and vegetables and to put these in the correct position a child needs to count and this reinforces the relationship between numerals and quantities. Just one of many new and innovative puzzles and games from Scotchi. All of the pieces are made from extremely durable polypropylene which is safe flexible and best of all washable so great for sticky fingers! There are 36 different pairs to match up and collect in this classic family favourite game. Place the cards randomly face down on the floor or table. It helps if the cards are placed in neat rows. Players take turns turning over only two cards at a time. If the cards match the pair can be collected. Should the cards not match they must be turned face down again and play continues in a clockwise direction to the next player. The aim is to try and remember where the cards are as this will help players find matching pairs on their next turn. The player with the most pairs when all the cards have been collected is the winner. The game play can be varied to suit different ages and abilities for younger children use fewer cards but you’ll be surprised at just how good youngsters are at this game – there is every chance that as their skills develop they will beat you! desc: Product Description Once upon a time there was someone who loved telling stories... well if you know that someone then theyll be a winner at playing The Story Telling Game! Whether they tell tall short fairy or scary stories this fast-paced game will be a best-seller for children aged six upwards who have a vivid imagination a competitive streak and are quick thinking. The Story Telling Game is a great birthday and Christmas gift and it not only encourages creativity but it will keep children entertained on rainy days and school holidays. Created for budding Jackanorys The Story Telling Game sees each player start with five words on their cards and when the clock starts the first players starts telling a story using one of their words. Then its the turn of the next player who has to incorporate one of their words into the former players story... and so it goes on with each player adding to the story with one of their words at a time until the buzzer declares that its The End for the player whos talking when the buzzer sounds. When this happens the player has to pick up all the cards used by the other players and begin a new story this time with the opening Twice upon a time. The story doesnt have to win awards or be a work of literary genius - it can be about anything but has to include one of the words on each of their cards. The Smiley Trump card adds a twist to the game as it can be used as any word and if a player is caught out by the buzzer the Smiley Trump means they get off scot-free and the next player has to collect all the cards. name: Boggle
desc: Product Description Great game in very good condition same design box but Parker is the maker not Hasbro the 3 minute word game for 1 or more players age 8+ fast dispatch UK SELLER Amazon.co.uk Review Boggle is a three-minute word game for any number of players (you can even play alone) and is suitable for anyone over the age of eight. The game includes the special Boggle tray which is the bottom part of the clear cube container containing 16 letter dice and a sand timer which lasts for three minutes--you must supply your own pens and paper. The dice are placed in the Boggle container and given a good shake. Players must then place the container upright to allow the dice to settle with one letter on each side facing up. The sand timer is set and you have to make out as many words as possible from the letters facing upwards before the sand timer runs out. The letters used must be from adjoining dice and you can only use each letter once in any word. Words can be singular or plural in form and can be in any tense so long as they appear in any standard English dictionary. In fact it is a good idea to have one of the main dictionaries of record to hand for when the inevitable disputes arise.There are some other minor rules all of which are explained in the directions for play (for example you arent allowed to have foreign words or abbreviations) but the game itself is quite uncomplicated. All you need to bring is a good vocabulary. As soon as the timer runs out every player stops writing immediately. Each player then takes it in turns to read out the list of words they have compiled. Any word that has been recorded by another player is discounted and does not score--other words score from one point for a three or four letter word up to a maximum of 11 points for any word of eight letters or more.To win the game you must be the first player to reach a pre-agreed score or the player who has the highest score after a pre-agreed number of rounds. This is a thinking game for adults and an ideal way to extend the vocabulary of the younger players. Ben King

Rules Amazon.co.uk Review Catchphrase based on the popular TV show is attractively designed caters for ages eight years and above and can be played by two people or teams. The game pack consists of four sets of cards and a timer. The packs are made up of groups of six double-sided cards. The face sides are numbered 160 and are complete catchphrase images. The reverse sides are part of a bigger image made up of the six cards. The reverse of the card is revealed on the playing board when a person or team guess the face catchphrase correctly. desc: Product Description this is a second edition and is a great game to play with family or friends Amazon.co.uk Review Ask the audience what they think of Who Wants to be a Millionaire? Based on the hit TV show that has pulled record audience figures around the world the game is much as it is onscreen: you must answer increasingly difficult general knowledge questions in sequence without getting any wrong to win larger and larger amounts of money (in this case fictional cash!). You have three lifelines 50-50 Ask the Audience and even Phone A Friend but once theyre gone youre on your own. The questions in this new version have been updated so even addicted players of the first edition will have plenty to go at. Cards replace Chris Tarrant and a board replaces the TV studio but otherwise the atmosphere can be every bit as electric as the real thing. So go on give it a try. You may just be the next paper Millionaire! --Sophie Lowe Each of these games contains a golden ticket giving the holder a chance to win a visit to the Who Wants to be a Millionaire studio to meet Chris Tarrant and play the game for real.

name: Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker Set - Includes Five Wooden Dice - Dice Game Set for Families
desc: Make your next family game night something truly special with the help of this Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker Set. With this simple game set you can play an endless number of dice games. In addition the dice shaker can be used along with board games to make sure that everyone is mixing the dice well and playing fairly! The set is great for adults kids and families to use for all types of play. The Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker Set is handmade dice set that is painstakingly crafted by woodworkers from Muradabad Uttar Pradesh in North India. The pieces are all made out of natural wood and have a handsome finish that shows off the intricate grain of the wood. The refinement and handsome details of the set makes this an attractive gift as well as something special that you can keep on display in your home in the den game room or family room. Barrel shaped to allow for maximum movement inside when you shake up the dice the Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker measures 2.5 inches in diameter at the top and 2.75 inches in diameter at the bottom. Standing at 3.5 inches in height the dice shaker is easy for adults and kids to grip tightly to shake. The shaker is topped with a metal lid which is etched with the word DICE. The lid stays securely in place when you shake but is easy to lift off when its time to roll the dice. Along with the Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker this handmade dice game includes a total of five dice. The dice feature a standard six-sided design with traditional dot patterning done with inlaid metal to match the shaker. The rounded corners allow the game dice to roll with ease. With the dice inside of the holder the entire shaker set weighs 142 grams. Shake things up the next time the family gathers for some quality time. Order the Handmade Wooden Dice Shaker Set and throw the dice in a whole new way or give someone special a unique fun gift that theyre sure to treasure! Add the dice game to your cart now!

name: Orchard Toys The Game of Ladybirds
desc: Product Description A very easy game that encourages counting skills. The 24 cards are placed on the table with spot sides uppermost. Throw the die and then pick up a card with a matching number of spots on it. Turn the card over and see how many little ladybirds are hiding on the leaf. Some leaves wont have any ladybirds on them and sometimes there wont be any cards left with the same number of spots as on the die. At the end of the game players have to count all their ladybirds and the winner is the player with the most. Or you can make it even more exciting by waiting until all the cards have been picked up before turning them over to count the ladybirds. One player could also be nominated to count everybodys ladybirds at the end. As well as helping with counting and addition skills this game also teaches observational and logic skills. It doesnt take too long to play so will hold a childs attention throughout the game. The cards can also be used to play other games such as Snap or Pairs or used for counting practice. There is also an educational guide on the box which shows how the game can enhance your childs education. The bright colours make this a visually appealing game and the durable recycled board with a wipe-clean finish means that the game will withstand plenty of use. It is suitable for 2 to 4 players aged 3 to 7.

The size and the structure of the box are just right for holding firmly in an adult palm. The lid of the box is crafted to fit well on the box and not slip off. Expert inlay work of brass on the wood to represent the numbers makes this dice box set exclusive. Wood artisans of Nagina in north India have handmade this dice box using skills passed on to them through several generations. Dice are small throwable objects with multiple resting positions used for generating random numbers. Dice are suitable as gambling devices for games likecraps and are also used in non-gambling tabletop games. A traditional die is a rounded cube with each of its six faces showing a different number of dots (pips) from 1 to 6. When thrown or rolled the die comes to rest showing on its upper surface a random integer from one to six each value being equally likely. A variety of similar devices are also described as dice such specialized dice may have polyhedral or irregular shapes and may have faces marked with symbols instead of numbers. They may be used to produce results other than one through six. A dice tray or a dice box is a piece of gaming equipment a tray used to contain thrown dice for gambling or board games.

name: DGT Cube - Worlds First Multiplayer Game Timer
desc: The DGT CUBE is a smart digital timing device that creates new dynamics in any game up to 6 players. There are five basic timing systems available with the DGT CUBE. Within a chosen timing system different times can be allocated to different players. At the end of a players turn the CUBE is passed on to the next player by turning the colour of the next player to the top. This stops the time of the last player and auto-starts the timing of the new player. During the game timing can be stopped and restarted by using the pause button. Use this for example to solve a dispute by consulting the dictionary in Scrabble or to fight a battle in RISK. The optional buzzer makes it easy to notice the approaching time limits. The DGT CUBE Timing Systems System 1: Move Timer Each player gets a fixed amount of time for each turn. The time per turn can be set to anything between 1 second and 10 minutes and is reset after a turn is completed i.e. the players receive the same amount of time again for the next turn. System2: Move Timer + Save If a player does not use all of the allocated time during his turn the unused time is saved and added to the time available for the next turn. For example if a player has one minute for his or her move and completes the turn after thirty seconds the remaining thirty seconds are automatically added as a bonus to the next turn and the player will have one minute and thirty seconds for the next turn. System 3: Count Down Game Timer A total time for the complete game is allocated to each player. The clock automatically starts and continues the count-down each time the players colour is turned to the top. If the time limit is reached i.e. the remaining time reaches zero the clock continues in the count-up mode. System 4: Count Up Game Timer By setting the CUBE to 0 hours and 00 minutes in the Game Timer Mode the CUBE registers the total time used by a player for each turn and adds this time to th

name: Peppa Pig Dominos
desc: Product Description There are 28 dominoes featuring all your favourite Peppa Pig characters. The numbers have been replaced by pictures so that young children can play the dominoes game and interact with the characters as they play and every tile is brightly coloured to make the game even more fun for your child. The first player to get rid of all their dominoes in the winner! It’s dominoes with a Peppa twist to keep children entertained while they learn - encouraging observation and matching skills.You begin by putting the dominoes face-down on a table or floor and shuffling them. Each player picks 5 tiles. Place the remaining tiles - face down - in a pile. The player with two identical pictures on a domino6 places this in the centre and the game begins. The next player - to the players left - tries to match one of his tiles with the one in the centre. The game continues in this way as each player takes a turn to try to create a chain of tiles. If you cannot place an identical tile down then you have to pick up a title from the stack. Tiles can only be placed at the start or end of other tiles to keep the chain going on. The 1st player to place all his tiles wins! Manufacturers Description 28 dominoes featuring your favourite Peppa Pig characters. desc: Product Description A lovely colourful domino game made from premium card. This classic game of Dominoes is based on the popular book series The Gruffalos Child. The story of The Gruffalo has been a long favourite among children for many years. This delightful version of dominoes is great fun for children who are fans of the Gruffalo series. Instead of boring old square dominoes the images on the pieces reflex the story of The Gruffalos Child. The game is educational helping with colour and character recognition counting and matching skills.Each Gruffalo image measures about 6cm x 3cm and the game plays in exactly the same way as normal dominoes. Each player takes a turn to try and match one of their tiles with the one in the centre. Tiles can only be placed at the start or end of other tiles to keep the chain going on. The first player to get rid of all their dominoes wins! In order to hide your playing pieces from the opposition you sit the pieces on their hind legs. The game is securely sealed together in a shrink wrapped box. The game is for 2 players or more and suitable for ages 3 years and up.
